body:
@srkukarni makes sense. I was worried if we do not call `ByteSize` first we won't get correct value of `GetCachedSize`. Your proposal looks good. We need to carefully make sure `ByteSize` will be called at the very first. Then use `GetCachedSize` all the way until we release it.

For perf, we may need more time to fix the viz.

This proposal may help #2253 as well.

@srkukarni @huijunw wanted to add this because when a topology just started, it seems physical plan message was so large that instance rejected it because of this limit.

This limit was defined here: https://github.com/twitter/heron/pull/2118/files

A solution we made internally at Twitter is to increase this value to 64Mbytes

@jerrypeng 
Thanks for sharing the context. I think we need to investigate the root cause, rather than commit something tentatively, since we don't know whether it does fix the issues, or potentially it can introduce other bugs.

If you need to skip this for local development, you could have it on a seprate branch or patch.

@objmagic I understand that. However why are we duplicating functionlity that already exists in Java. Shouldn't the pathway be
1. If jar is regular file, continue as before
2. If jar is uri of some sort, invoke a downloader(analogous to the uploader). I believe the downloader functionality already exists in the java spi side of things.

@huijunw 
I think `statefulstorage` is for the backend to store checkpoints in stateful processing.
And uploader/downloader are for topology tarball storage.

@huijunwu 

As @maosongfu pointed out, this issue is for using bookkeeper for storing topology jars.

I have a pull request for use bookkeeper as the statefulstorage. it is coming out soon.
